Note: Ruby to HIR Translator for Translation Translation System
Note: Converts Ruby AST to High-level Intermediate Representation

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/ruby/ruby_parser.runa" as RubyParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/ruby/ruby_lexer.runa" as RubyLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/ruby/ruby_semantic.runa" as RubySemantic
@Reasoning:
Ruby's translation needs three stacked context pointers (class / method / block) so nested defs, methods inside blocks, and closures can be linked back to their enclosing scope without re-walking the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six 8-byte fields: symbol table dictionary, current lexical scope, accumulator list of HIR nodes, plus the three context pointers (class_context, method_context, block_context) used as a manual scope stack during translation.
@End Implementation

Type called "RubyToHIRTranslator":
    symbol_table as Integer  Note: Maps symbols to HIR nodes
    current_scope as Integer  Note: Current scope context
    hir_nodes as Integer  Note: List of generated HIR nodes
    class_context as Integer  Note: Current class being translated
    method_context as Integer  Note: Current method being translated
    block_context as Integer  Note: Current block being translated
End Type

@Reasoning:
The translator must start in the "global" lexical scope with all three context pointers nulled so the first class/method/block entered initialises them rather than inheriting stale state.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Construct a RubyToHIRTranslator with an empty symbol-table dict, a fresh "global"-named scope, an empty hir_nodes accumulator, and class_context / method_context / block_context all set to 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_ruby_to_hir_translator" returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Ruby to HIR translator instance

    Let translator be a value of type RubyToHIRTranslator with
        symbol_table as proc create_dict,
        current_scope as proc create_scope with "global",
        hir_nodes as proc create_list,
        class_context as 0,
        method_context as 0,
        block_context as 0

    Return translator
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's AST has 40+ node kinds covering classes, modules, methods, control flow, exceptions, metaprogramming, and literals; a single dispatcher keeps every recursive call site funnel through one entry point.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Match on ast.node_type and route to the corresponding translate_* helper. Unknown tags fall through to create_hir_unknown so unsupported constructs survive as inspectable placeholders rather than silently disappearing.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_ruby_to_hir" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby AST to HIR with complete feature support

    Let node_type be ast.node_type

    Match node_type:
        When AST_PROGRAM from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_program with translator, ast
        When AST_CLASS from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_class with translator, ast
        When AST_MODULE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_module with translator, ast
        When AST_METHOD from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_method with translator, ast
        When AST_BLOCK from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_block with translator, ast
        When AST_IF from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_if with translator, ast
        When AST_UNLESS from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_unless with translator, ast
        When AST_WHILE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_while with translator, ast
        When AST_UNTIL from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_until with translator, ast
        When AST_FOR from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_for with translator, ast
        When AST_CASE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_case with translator, ast
        When AST_BEGIN_RESCUE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_begin_rescue with translator, ast
        When AST_RESCUE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_rescue with translator, ast
        When AST_ENSURE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_ensure with translator, ast
        When AST_YIELD from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_yield with translator, ast
        When AST_LAMBDA from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_lambda with translator, ast
        When AST_PROC from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_proc with translator, ast
        When AST_ASSIGNMENT from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_assignment with translator, ast
        When AST_METHOD_CALL from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_method_call with translator, ast
        When AST_SUPER_CALL from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_super_call with translator, ast
        When AST_SELF from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_self with translator, ast
        When AST_IDENTIFIER from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_identifier with translator, ast
        When AST_CONSTANT from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_constant with translator, ast
        When AST_INSTANCE_VAR from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_instance_var with translator, ast
        When AST_CLASS_VAR from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_class_var with translator, ast
        When AST_GLOBAL_VAR from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_global_var with translator, ast
        When AST_SYMBOL from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_symbol with translator, ast
        When AST_STRING from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_string with translator, ast
        When AST_INTERPOLATED_STRING from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_interpolated_string with translator, ast
        When AST_NUMBER from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_number with translator, ast
        When AST_ARRAY from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_array with translator, ast
        When AST_HASH from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_hash with translator, ast
        When AST_RANGE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_range with translator, ast
        When AST_BINARY_OP from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_binary_op with translator, ast
        When AST_UNARY_OP from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_unary_op with translator, ast
        When AST_RETURN from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_return with translator, ast
        When AST_BREAK from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_break with translator, ast
        When AST_NEXT from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_next with translator, ast
        When AST_INCLUDE from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_include with translator, ast
        When AST_EXTEND from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_extend with translator, ast
        When AST_ALIAS from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_alias with translator, ast
        When AST_UNDEF from RubyParser:
            Return proc translate_undef with translator, ast
        Otherwise:
            Return proc create_hir_unknown from ast
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Ruby AST_PROGRAM root is the entire .rb file; lifting it into an HIR module node with body="main" gives downstream consumers a uniform module-shaped envelope regardless of source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=module with name="main". Iterate every top-level child via translate_ruby_to_hir, push non-null results into the body statements List, attach at "body".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_program" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby program to HIR module

    Let hir_module be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "node_type", "module"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "name", "main"

    Let statements be proc create_list

    Note: Translate all top-level statements
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index
        Let hir_child be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, child

        If hir_child is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list with statements, hir_child
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "body", statements

    Return hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby classes carry a name, optional superclass, mixins (include/extend), and a body whose own statements may further nest classes; saving and restoring class_context implements lexical-class tracking through arbitrarily deep nesting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=class. Copy the name attribute, recurse into the optional superclass. Save the current class_context, set it to this class, push a "class" lexical scope. Walk body children translating each; then extract include/extend statements via extract_mixins. Pop the scope and restore class_context.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in class body length plus the cost of every nested translation; one allocation per HIR node.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_class" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby class with inheritance and mixins to HIR

    Let hir_class be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_class, "node_type", "class"

    Note: Get class name
    Let class_name be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "name"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_class, "name", class_name

    Note: Handle inheritance
    Let superclass be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "superclass"
    If superclass is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_superclass be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, superclass
        proc set_dict_value with hir_class, "superclass", hir_superclass
    End If

    Note: Set class context
    Let previous_class be translator.class_context
    Set translator.class_context to hir_class

    Note: Create class scope
    proc push_scope with translator, "class"

    Note: Translate class body
    Let body_statements be proc create_list
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index
        Let hir_child be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, child

        If hir_child is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list with body_statements, hir_child
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_class, "body", body_statements

    Note: Handle included modules and extended modules
    proc extract_mixins with translator, hir_class, body_statements

    Note: Restore previous context
    proc pop_scope from translator
    Set translator.class_context to previous_class

    Return hir_class
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby modules act as namespaces and mixin containers - structurally similar to classes but without inheritance or instantiation - so HIR represents them with a "module" tag distinct from class.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=module. Copy the name attribute, push a "module" lexical scope, recursively translate body children into the body List, pop the scope.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_module" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby module to HIR

    Let hir_module be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "node_type", "module"

    Note: Get module name
    Let module_name be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "name"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "name", module_name

    Note: Create module scope
    proc push_scope with translator, "module"

    Note: Translate module body
    Let body_statements be proc create_list
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index
        Let hir_child be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, child

        If hir_child is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list with body_statements, hir_child
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "body", body_statements

    Note: Restore previous scope
    proc pop_scope from translator

    Return hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby methods need parameter list lowering (positional + splat + double-splat + block + defaults), implicit-return wrapping, and proper method_context tracking so nested yields and blocks resolve to the right enclosing method.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=function with name and translated parameters. Save method_context, set it to this method, push a "method" scope. Translate body children, attach as "body". Run ensure_implicit_return to wrap the last statement in an implicit "return" node. Restore scope and method_context.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_method" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby method with blocks and metaprogramming features

    Let hir_method be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "node_type", "function"

    Note: Get method name
    Let method_name be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "name"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "name", method_name

    Note: Handle parameters
    Let parameters be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "parameters"
    If parameters is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_params be proc translate_method_parameters with translator, parameters
        proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "parameters", hir_params
    End If

    Note: Set method context
    Let previous_method be translator.method_context
    Set translator.method_context to hir_method

    Note: Create method scope
    proc push_scope with translator, "method"

    Note: Translate method body
    Let body_statements be proc create_list
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index
        Let hir_child be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, child

        If hir_child is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list with body_statements, hir_child
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_method, "body", body_statements

    Note: Handle implicit return
    proc ensure_implicit_return with hir_method, body_statements

    Note: Restore previous context
    proc pop_scope from translator
    Set translator.method_context to previous_method

    Return hir_method
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby parameters come in five flavours that must be distinguished in HIR for correct call-site lowering: regular, splat (*args), double_splat (**kwargs), block (&blk), and optional defaults.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each parameter, create a Dictionary with name, then check the parser-set attributes splat/double_splat/block in order and tag the parameter with the first match (or "regular"). If a default value exists, recursively translate it and attach at "default".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_method_parameters" takes translator as Integer, params as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby method parameters including splats and defaults

    Let hir_params be proc create_list
    Let param_count be proc get_list_size from params
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than param_count:
        Let param be proc get_list_item with params, index
        Let hir_param be proc create_hir_dict

        Note: Get parameter name
        Let param_name be proc get_node_attribute with param, "name"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "name", param_name

        Note: Handle parameter types
        If proc get_node_attribute with param, "splat" is not equal to 0:
            proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "type", "splat"
        Otherwise If proc get_node_attribute with param, "double_splat" is not equal to 0:
            proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "type", "double_splat"
        Otherwise If proc get_node_attribute with param, "block" is not equal to 0:
            proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "type", "block"
        Otherwise:
            proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "type", "regular"
        End If

        Note: Handle default values
        Let default_value be proc get_node_attribute with param, "default"
        If default_value is not equal to 0:
            Let hir_default be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, default_value
            proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "default", hir_default
        End If

        proc add_to_list with hir_params, hir_param
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return hir_params
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Ruby method call binds an optional receiver, a method name, an argument list, and an optional trailing block; capturing all four as discrete HIR fields lets the lowering stage dispatch send/call mechanics uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=call. If the call node has a first child, translate it as receiver. Copy ast.value into "method". If arguments attribute present, translate via translate_arguments. If block attribute present, recursively translate as the block payload.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_method_call" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby method call with receivers, arguments, and blocks

    Let hir_call be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_call, "node_type", "call"

    Note: Handle receiver
    Let receiver_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    If receiver_count is greater than 0:
        Let receiver be proc get_list_item with ast.children, 0
        Let hir_receiver be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, receiver
        proc set_dict_value with hir_call, "receiver", hir_receiver
    End If

    Note: Set method name
    proc set_dict_value with hir_call, "method", ast.value

    Note: Handle arguments
    Let arguments be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "arguments"
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_args be proc translate_arguments with translator, arguments
        proc set_dict_value with hir_call, "arguments", hir_args
    End If

    Note: Handle block
    Let block be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "block"
    If block is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_block be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, block
        proc set_dict_value with hir_call, "block", hir_block
    End If

    Return hir_call
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby blocks "{|x| ...}" / "do |x| ... end" carry their own parameter list and capture the enclosing local scope; recording block_context lets nested yields and the new lexical scope cooperate correctly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=block. Map each parameter name into a small "name"-only Dictionary attached at "parameters". Save block_context, set it to this block, push a "block" scope. Translate body children. Restore block_context and pop scope.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_block" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby block with parameters and closure semantics

    Let hir_block be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_block, "node_type", "block"

    Note: Handle block parameters
    Let parameters be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "parameters"
    If parameters is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_params be proc create_list
        Let param_count be proc get_list_size from parameters
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than param_count:
            Let param_name be proc get_list_item with parameters, index
            Let hir_param be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with hir_param, "name", param_name
            proc add_to_list with hir_params, hir_param
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc set_dict_value with hir_block, "parameters", hir_params
    End If

    Note: Set block context
    Let previous_block be translator.block_context
    Set translator.block_context to hir_block

    Note: Create block scope
    proc push_scope with translator, "block"

    Note: Translate block body
    Let body_statements be proc create_list
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    Set index to 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index
        Let hir_child be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, child

        If hir_child is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list with body_statements, hir_child
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_block, "body", body_statements

    Note: Restore previous context
    proc pop_scope from translator
    Set translator.block_context to previous_block

    Return hir_block
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's if/elsif/else chains an arbitrary number of elsif clauses; capturing each elsif separately rather than nesting if-else in HIR preserves the source structure for back-translation and error reporting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=conditional with translated condition. Translate then_body via translate_statement_list. For each elsif clause, recursively translate and append to the elsif_clauses List. If an else_body attribute exists, translate it via translate_statement_list and attach.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_if" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby if statement with elsif and else clauses

    Let hir_if be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "node_type", "conditional"

    Note: Translate condition
    Let condition be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "condition"
    Let hir_condition be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, condition
    proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "condition", hir_condition

    Note: Translate then body
    Let then_body be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "then_body"
    Let hir_then_body be proc translate_statement_list with translator, then_body
    proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "then_body", hir_then_body

    Note: Handle elsif clauses
    Let elsif_clauses be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "elsif_clauses"
    If elsif_clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_elsif_clauses be proc create_list
        Let elsif_count be proc get_list_size from elsif_clauses
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than elsif_count:
            Let elsif_clause be proc get_list_item with elsif_clauses, index
            Let hir_elsif be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, elsif_clause
            proc add_to_list with hir_elsif_clauses, hir_elsif
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "elsif_clauses", hir_elsif_clauses
    End If

    Note: Handle else clause
    Let else_body be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "else_body"
    If else_body is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_else_body be proc translate_statement_list with translator, else_body
        proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "else_body", hir_else_body
    End If

    Return hir_if
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby assignment is uniform across regular "=", compound ("+=", "||=", etc.), and multiple-assignment forms; storing the operator text plus translated LHS/RHS lets a single HIR shape cover all of them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=assignment with operator copied from ast.value. Translate children[0] as "target", children[1] as "value".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_assignment" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby assignment with various operators

    Let hir_assign be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "node_type", "assignment"

    Note: Get assignment operator
    proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "operator", ast.value

    Note: Translate left side (variable)
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let lhs be proc get_list_item with ast.children, 0
        Let hir_lhs be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, lhs
        proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "target", hir_lhs
    End If

    Note: Translate right side (value)
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let rhs be proc get_list_item with ast.children, 1
        Let hir_rhs be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, rhs
        proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "value", hir_rhs
    End If

    Return hir_assign
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby array literals "[a, b, c]" carry their elements as direct children; the HIR shape mirrors that with a "node_type=array_literal" envelope and a children list of translated elements.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=array_literal. Recursively translate every child and append to the elements List attached at "elements".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_array" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby array literal to HIR

    Let hir_array be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_array, "node_type", "array_literal"

    Let elements be proc create_list
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let element be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index
        Let hir_element be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, element
        proc add_to_list with elements, hir_element
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_array, "elements", elements

    Return hir_array
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser flattens hash literals "{k => v, ...}" into a child list of alternating key/value nodes; the translator reconstitutes them into discrete key/value pair Dictionaries so HIR consumers do not need to know the flattening trick.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=hash_literal. Iterate children in steps of two; pair index/index+1 as key/value, recursively translate both, and append a Dictionary with key/value keys to the pairs List.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_hash" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby hash literal to HIR

    Let hir_hash be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_hash, "node_type", "hash_literal"

    Let pairs be proc create_list
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    Let index be 0

    Note: Process key-value pairs
    While index is less than child_count:
        If index plus 1 is less than child_count:
            Let key be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index
            Let value be proc get_list_item with ast.children, index plus 1

            Let hir_key be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, key
            Let hir_value be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, value

            Let pair be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with pair, "key", hir_key
            proc set_dict_value with pair, "value", hir_value

            proc add_to_list with pairs, pair
        End If

        Set index to index plus 2
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_hash, "pairs", pairs

    Return hir_hash
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby symbols ":foo" are interned immutable identifiers; preserving them as a distinct HIR kind (rather than collapsing to strings) keeps optimisation passes able to leverage their identity-equality property.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=symbol with the symbol's lexeme copied to "value".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_symbol" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby symbol to HIR

    Let hir_symbol be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_symbol, "node_type", "symbol"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_symbol, "value", ast.value

    Return hir_symbol
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby interpolated strings ""hello #{expr}"" mix literal text and embedded expressions; lifting them into a parts list with text/expression sub-nodes lets lowering emit appropriate string-build calls.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=interpolated_string. Parse the raw value via parse_interpolation_parts into alternating text/expression parts. For each part: text -> wrap in a string_literal Dictionary; expression -> reparse via parse_ruby_expression and recursively translate. Attach the resulting list at "parts".
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Re-parsing embedded expressions requires that parse_ruby_expression treat its input as untrusted source code; misuse can let an attacker who controls the string trigger arbitrary parser behaviour.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_interpolated_string" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby interpolated string to HIR

    Let hir_interp be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_interp, "node_type", "interpolated_string"

    Note: Parse interpolation expressions from the string
    Let parts be proc parse_interpolation_parts with ast.value
    Let hir_parts be proc create_list

    Let part_count be proc get_list_size from parts
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than part_count:
        Let part be proc get_list_item with parts, index
        Let part_type be proc get_dict_value with part, "type"

        If part_type is equal to "text":
            Let text_node be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with text_node, "node_type", "string_literal"
            proc set_dict_value with text_node, "value", proc get_dict_value with part, "content"
            proc add_to_list with hir_parts, text_node
        Otherwise If part_type is equal to "expression":
            Note: Parse the embedded expression
            Let expr_text be proc get_dict_value with part, "content"
            Let expr_ast be proc parse_ruby_expression from expr_text
            Let hir_expr be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, expr_ast
            proc add_to_list with hir_parts, hir_expr
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_interp, "parts", hir_parts

    Return hir_interp
End Process

@Reasoning:
"yield" hands control to the block attached to the surrounding method call; HIR records the optional argument list so that the lowering stage can wire it to the block's parameters.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=yield. If an arguments attribute is present, translate via translate_arguments and attach.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_yield" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby yield statement to HIR

    Let hir_yield be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_yield, "node_type", "yield"

    Note: Handle yield arguments
    Let arguments be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "arguments"
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_args be proc translate_arguments with translator, arguments
        proc set_dict_value with hir_yield, "arguments", hir_args
    End If

    Return hir_yield
End Process

@Reasoning:
"super" dispatches to the same-named method on the superclass; HIR captures only the arguments (the method name and receiver are implicit), since downstream lowering must reconstruct them from the lexical context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=super_call. If arguments attribute present, translate via translate_arguments and attach.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_super_call" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby super call to HIR

    Let hir_super be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_super, "node_type", "super_call"

    Note: Handle super arguments
    Let arguments be proc get_node_attribute with ast, "arguments"
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_args be proc translate_arguments with translator, arguments
        proc set_dict_value with hir_super, "arguments", hir_args
    End If

    Return hir_super
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby treats most "operators" as method calls on the LHS, but they appear in the AST as binary_op nodes; HIR keeps them tagged distinctly to let constant-folding and arithmetic-lowering passes match on operator text directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=binary_operation with operator copied from ast.value. If at least two children exist, recursively translate children[0] as "left" and children[1] as "right".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_binary_op" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby binary operation to HIR

    Let hir_binop be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_binop, "node_type", "binary_operation"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_binop, "operator", ast.value

    Note: Translate operands
    Let child_count be proc get_list_size with ast.children
    If child_count is greater than or equal to 2:
        Let left be proc get_list_item with ast.children, 0
        Let right be proc get_list_item with ast.children, 1

        Let hir_left be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, left
        Let hir_right be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, right

        proc set_dict_value with hir_binop, "left", hir_left
        proc set_dict_value with hir_binop, "right", hir_right
    End If

    Return hir_binop
End Process

@Reasoning:
In Ruby the variable kind is determined by the identifier's sigil/case: @x instance, @@x class, $x global, X (uppercase first) constant, plain lowercase local. Encoding the kind in HIR avoids re-classification by every downstream pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged node_type=identifier with name copied from ast.value. Inspect the first character: "@" then "@" -> class_variable, "@" alone -> instance_variable, "$" -> global_variable, uppercase letter -> constant, anything else -> local_variable. Store the classification at "variable_type".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_identifier" takes translator as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate Ruby identifier to HIR

    Let hir_id be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_id, "node_type", "identifier"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_id, "name", ast.value

    Note: Check for variable type based on naming convention
    Let first_char be proc char_at with ast.value, 0

    If first_char is equal to "@":
        If proc char_at with ast.value, 1 is equal to "@":
            proc set_dict_value with hir_id, "variable_type", "class_variable"
        Otherwise:
            proc set_dict_value with hir_id, "variable_type", "instance_variable"
        End If
    Otherwise If first_char is equal to "$":
        proc set_dict_value with hir_id, "variable_type", "global_variable"
    Otherwise If proc is_uppercase with first_char is equal to 1:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_id, "variable_type", "constant"
    Otherwise:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_id, "variable_type", "local_variable"
    End If

    Return hir_id
End Process

Note: Helper processes for Ruby to HIR translation

@Reasoning:
HIR Dictionaries follow a 32-byte block layout (count / capacity / keys ptr / values ptr); centralising the allocation in one helper keeps the size constant in one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Request a 32-byte block from Layout and return the raw pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_hir_dict" returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR dictionary node
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR Lists use a 16-byte header (count + storage pointer); the helper keeps the size constant adjacent to its sibling create_hir_dict.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Request a 16-byte block from Layout and return the raw pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_list" returns Integer:
    Note: Create list for HIR storage
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
The translator's internal symbol-table dictionary uses a smaller 24-byte header than HIR Dictionaries because it does not need to track the same metadata.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Request a 24-byte block from Layout and return the raw pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_dict" returns Integer:
    Note: Create dictionary for storage
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
if/elsif/else bodies are lists of statements; uniform translation through one helper keeps the conditional translator simple.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate an output List, walk the source list translating each entry via translate_ruby_to_hir, append non-null results.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_statement_list" takes translator as Integer, statements as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate list of Ruby statements to HIR

    Let hir_statements be proc create_list
    Let stmt_count be proc get_list_size from statements
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than stmt_count:
        Let statement be proc get_list_item with statements, index
        Let hir_stmt be proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, statement

        If hir_stmt is not equal to 0:
            proc add_to_list with hir_statements, hir_stmt
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return hir_statements
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby methods implicitly return the last expression evaluated; making that explicit in HIR (as a return node with implicit="true") lets downstream optimisers treat returns uniformly regardless of source style.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the body has at least one statement and the last is not already a "return", construct an implicit-return Dictionary wrapping that statement (with implicit="true") and overwrite the last list entry with the wrapper.
@End Implementation

Process called "ensure_implicit_return" takes hir_method as Integer, body_statements as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Ensure Ruby's implicit return semantics in HIR

    Let stmt_count be proc get_list_size from body_statements

    If stmt_count is greater than 0:
        Let last_stmt be proc get_list_item with body_statements, stmt_count minus 1
        Let stmt_type be proc get_dict_value with last_stmt, "node_type"

        Note: If last statement is not already a return, wrap it in implicit return
        If stmt_type is not equal to "return":
            Let implicit_return be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with implicit_return, "node_type", "return"
            proc set_dict_value with implicit_return, "value", last_stmt
            proc set_dict_value with implicit_return, "implicit", "true"

            Note: Replace last statement with implicit return
            proc set_list_item with body_statements, stmt_count minus 1, implicit_return
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Ruby's mixin mechanism uses include/extend calls inside the class body; hoisting them into dedicated includes/extends lists on the class node makes the mixin graph directly queryable without rescanning the body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk body_statements; sort statements whose node_type equals "include" into the includes List and "extend" into the extends List. After scanning, if either list is non-empty, attach it to hir_class at "includes" / "extends".
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_mixins" takes translator as Integer, hir_class as Integer, body_statements as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extract include and extend statements from class body

    Let includes be proc create_list
    Let extends be proc create_list
    Let stmt_count be proc get_list_size from body_statements
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt be proc get_list_item with body_statements, index
        Let stmt_type be proc get_dict_value with stmt, "node_type"

        If stmt_type is equal to "include":
            proc add_to_list with includes, stmt
        Otherwise If stmt_type is equal to "extend":
            proc add_to_list with extends, stmt
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    If proc get_list_size with includes is greater than 0:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_class, "includes", includes
    End If

    If proc get_list_size with extends is greater than 0:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_class, "extends", extends
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The scope stack is updated through one helper so callers do not have to know the underlying scope linkage strategy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a new scope of the given kind ("class", "module", "method", "block") linked to the translator's current scope, then make it current.
@End Implementation

Process called "push_scope" takes translator as Integer, scope_type as String returns Integer:
    Note: Push new scope onto translator's scope stack
    Note: Implementation  create new scope and link to parent
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pop is the symmetric helper for push; centralising it keeps the stack discipline invariant - every push has exactly one matching pop in the translate_* helpers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Restore the translator's current scope pointer to the parent of the current scope.
@End Implementation

Process called "pop_scope" takes translator as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Pop current scope from translator's scope stack
    Note: Implementation  restore previous scope
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier classification needs to detect ASCII uppercase letters as the marker for Ruby constants; a tight code-point predicate is faster than a String comparison.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Get the integer code point of the input character and return 1 if it lies in 65..90 (A..Z), 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_uppercase" takes char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is uppercase
    Let code be proc char_code from char
    Return code is greater than or equal to 65 and code is less than or equal to 90
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public single-arg facade invoked by the translation dispatcher's
LANG_RUBY arm. Wires the full source -> HIR pipeline: RubyLexer's
create_ruby_lexer + tokenize_ruby produce the token list, RubyParser's
create_ruby_parser wraps those tokens, parse_ruby walks them into an
AST_PROGRAM root, the optional semantic pass (dynamic-type tracking,
scope analysis) validates the AST without mutating its shape, and
translate_ruby_to_hir lowers it into HIR through a freshly constructed
RubyToHIRTranslator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
lexer = RubyLexer.create_ruby_lexer(source); tokens = RubyLexer.tokenize_ruby(lexer);
parser = RubyParser.create_ruby_parser(tokens); ast = RubyParser.parse_ruby(parser);
if ast == 0 return 0; analyzer = RubySemantic.create_ruby_semantic_analyzer();
if non-zero, run RubySemantic.analyze_ruby_ast(analyzer, ast) -- the result is
discarded because the translator walks the same AST regardless and surfaces
its own errors. translator = create_ruby_to_hir_translator; if 0 return 0;
return translate_ruby_to_hir(translator, ast). Lifetimes are bounded by the
calling translate_to_hir frame.
@End Implementation

Process called "ruby_to_hir_from_source" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_ruby_lexer from RubyLexer with source_code
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tokens be proc tokenize_ruby from RubyLexer with lexer
    If tokens is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_ruby_parser from RubyParser with tokens
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ast be proc parse_ruby from RubyParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let analyzer be proc create_ruby_semantic_analyzer from RubySemantic
    If analyzer is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_ruby_ast from RubySemantic with analyzer, ast
    End If

    Let translator be proc create_ruby_to_hir_translator
    If translator is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc translate_ruby_to_hir with translator, ast
End Process